< review>
Quaint little boba place that is near the downtown area with plenty of parking and indoor seating. Service was quick and efficient and there was almost no line or waiting required. Not too heavily trafficked. The boba on the other hand was slightly disappointing. Tea was not brewed with a very strong consistency and the boba's texture was not quite right. The egg pudding was also cloyingly sweet.<//review>

<Text>BOOK WITH NINA!!!

Considering that this was my first tattoo, I was very new to the world of ink and felt very uninformed. I knew one thing and one things only; what I wanted and where. However, I struggled to find an artist who’s style and technique matched what I was looking for. That was, until I came across Nina’s portfolio. I decided to walk into Devoted Ink and speak to her directly about what I wanted and what she thought of my idea. Within 10 seconds of meeting her I knew she was the artist I’d been searching for! She gave me such insightful comments on the piece I had showed her for reference and immediately assured me she was confident we could craft something remarkable. I booked my appointment that day and returned a couple weeks later for my tattoo. It was then that I was able to see the original piece that Nina had created, and I was floored! It was beyond what I was expecting and I could instantly identify how much time and effort she put into crafting something so unique and fitting to what I had envisioned.
Throughout the session, Nina made the experience so fun and personal to the point where I had even forgotten she was in the process of tattooing! She also made a point of showing me the progress throughout the session so I could see the transformation from the second I sat down in the chair to the second I stood up with the finished piece.
I could not be more pleased with the way my tattoo turned out and I have made the decision to turn the shoulder piece into a full sleeve. Of course, I’ve asked Nina to do it exclusively because her talent and work emulate everything I want for the progression of this incredible tattoo.
However, mere words do not do her work justice. I strongly urge anyone reading this to contact Nina about any piece you want or may be considering. You will not be disappointed!!</Text><pictures>None</pictures><response>None< /response>< gmap_id>

If you want a custom tattoo, done by a true artist, in a clean shop with a great atmosphere then you've got to go to Devoted Ink. I've been in and around other shops and this is by far the best experience I've had.
After searching the IE for good shops and consulting with some artists I came across Devoted Ink. I had to consult with them over email and phone at first due to them being 45 minutes away but they were very helpful.
When I met with the artist, Derek, he did a great job of talking through my design ideas and we came up with a design that far surpassed what I'd planned on. He drew up the art based on photos (not generic flash) had me look over it (it was great) and got to work.
Because I'm busy and I live farther away he was willing to get it done in one sitting. 11 hours later I walked out with two tattoos that I am very proud of, that my kids love (they represent them) and I get compliments on all the time.</review>

<rating>1</rating><Text>Made a $100.00 deposit, submitted my tattoo idea, spoke to the artist I chose (still works there) and had everything set up. Then, two days before my appointment, he tells me that I wasn’t able to get what I originally wanted; I could choose between picking another piece/idea or get my deposit back. So, I drove from Camp Pendleton to Temecula to get my deposit back. I reached their parlor and was denied my refund. I contacted my artist, telling him about the situation. He then asked me when my appointment was to which I replied in two days. He immediately says that there is a 48 hour cancellation policy, that my deposit was non-refundable because I was in that 48 hour window. Not once was this mentioned before. I find it odd that all of a sudden, despite our conversations, that there was a convenient cancellation policy that matched the exact time that I had to get my deposit back.

I was really looking forward to getting work done at this parlor for reasons such as tattoo quality, high artistic skill, area cleanliness, and religious background. Ultimately, I was $100.00 short, had a Taco Bell taco (or 5) that told my stomach I needed to pull over at the next gas station, and had a heavy traffic ride back home. This was back in 2015, I believe. I’m still $100.00 short and have learned my lesson on eating taco bell on the road.

Please don’t let me review make you think twice about approaching this parlor or the artists. They produce quality work and have one of the nicest shops I’ve seen in years. Just be vigilant on keeping in contact with your artist and your appointment.< /Text>< Pics>

< userid>
100973507282700835264< /userid>
< user_name>
Diane Mac< /user_name>
<Date>1382121016376< /Date><rate>5</rate>< Text>
LOVE THIS PLACE!
I wanted to cover up a tattoo I got in 1978 and Devoted Ink happened to be on my route from San Diego to Riverside so I just dropped in. Although Matt was tattooing someone he took a few minutes to do a consult. He looked at my old ink and after I told him what I had in mind he searched the internet and showed me some ideas....paintings, not other people’s tattoos. I told him I trusted him and we scheduled an appt for 10/10 (he is normally booked several weeks in advance).
I arrived yesterday at 11 AM as scheduled, he showed me the painting he'd chosen and after getting my approval he started setting up which took about 45 minutes.
I spent the next 6 hours straddling a chair, chatting with Rob (the other tattoo artist) and Rob's client, who was getting a Phoenix to support his wife who is battling cancer. Rob ordered pizza for us about 3 hours into it and also put something called Blue Ice on the work he'd already done which made the next 3 hours a lot less painful.
Before I left Matt provided me with an after care kit for $20 and a printed list of instructions.
One thing I LOVE about Devoted Ink is their faith. They love God and it is obvious in the way they relate to people that that they live their faith. In the 6 hours I was there I heard phone conversations, consultations and the normal conversation that goes on between co-workers and neighbors in the strip mall they work with and all reflected the love of God. These guys are awesome.</Text>

< text>
My husband and I walked into Devoted ink 3 months ago to make an appointment for today. We told Matt we would like to come in June 15th at 1pm. He told us that it was his moms birthday but he could fit us in real fast since my husband was getting a ring tattoo and it wouldn't take long.

2 months later we get a call from Matt saying someone scheduled us on his Moms birthday and he we needed to reschedule. Even though he was the one who had scheduled us on his Moms birthday when we went into the store. He then put us down for Wednesday June 12th at 5pm. Which we could not do because we would be on our honeymoon until Saturday morning. He expected us to leave our honeymoon to come back and get the tattoo because he did not want to do it the day HE scheduled us for 2 MONTHS ago!

I was really upset so I called up Matt and told him we needed to be there on Saturday like planned. We would be on our way back from our Honeymoon and we do not live around here. He told us he would put us on the schedule for One saturday with a different tattoo artist. which was fine.

Wednesday June 12th comes and while we are on our honeymoon Matt calls us and asks if we can come in at 3pm that day instead of five. So he did not reschedule us for Saturday like he said he would. I was pretty upset at this point. making an appointment should not be this complicated. But it is for these people. I told him I called and he told me we were coming in Saturday at one. He quickly remembered and said oh yeahhh. Then said we cant come in at that time but would have to come in at 10am Saturday.

We leave our hotel room early in the morning to get to this devoted ink place 3 hours before our original appointment. We get there on time a little before ten and no one is there. We wait 20 mins until finally the closed sign turns to open. We walk in fill out paper work and then waited about 35 mins for the guy to set up all his stuff. Shouldn't it all be ready by the time we walked in?

The guy at the front started talking about Matt and why he wasn't there today. Turns out it was not his moms birthday so they said but his birthday. Overall this place was a nightmare. They did not want to do the tattoo design my husband wanted because it was too complex. Even though we have seen tons of people with tattoos very similar to the one he wanted. They told him they could not Tattoo the insides of the fingers but then ended up doing that anyways.

They didn't put a wrap on it or anything. And on top of all this. The price they told us 3 months ago was not what they charged. They charged 10$ more and added a .03% charge for using a credit card.</text>

<review>Beautiful, relaxing outdoor seating with patio umbrellas at most tables as well as a covered patio area. Sit amongst their vineyard. They specialize in Sangiovese varietal wines, including bianco, rosato and traditional red styles. During the summer they also often have a slushee machine that they use to make wine slushees. Friendly staff that will answer your questions, but don’t overly pester you while you enjoy their scenery and wine.
Their wine tasting flights range from $10-15 for non-members. Glasses of wine range from $7.50-10.</review><Name>Catherine Lee<//Name>< rating>

<Pictures>None< /Pictures><Review>Fabulous Sangiovese wines, friendly and pleasant folks, and beautiful vistas in Plymouth CA. Had such an enjoyable time, I joined their Big Nut Wine Club. A funny touch is the old Doggie Diner mascot head. Vino Noceto is a definite must visit when wine tasting in Amador County. Sierra Foothills Vineyards and Wineries are beautiful and the wines are outstanding.

I returned for a second visit. We drank Vino Noceto Zinfandel OGP  by the glass while having a picnic which we brought with us. The wine made from vines that date to 1869 is a wonderful experience and its taste is extraordinary.  Definitely worth a purchase by any folks who enjoy Zinfandel. The people at Vino Noceto couldn't be nicer.  I will always return there for the wine, the folks, the vistas and the  chill vibe.

Bellissimo!< /Review><Time>1602172237952<//Time><response>{'time': 1604435939441, 'text': 'Hi Curley Curley, we are so glad you enjoyed your visit, welcome to the Nutty Club. <Date>1600477580185< /Date>< review>
I came down here to buy a used car around the corner and stumbled upon John’s just by chance and saw the reviews and decided to go here.

Not only is this mom and pop shop full of totally genuine people, they were extremely professional and provided me with a more than thorough inspection at a VERY affordable price.

That’s great and all but what happened next floored me.

I got talking to John, the owner and explained to him I had driven down from Santa Barbara - over 2 hours away - to check out this car and he inquired as to what I was going to do with it if I had driven down in a car already. I told him I wasn’t really sure and hadn’t figured it out quite yet if I purchased the used car. With no where to store the car and not familiar with the area, John offered to store the car INSIDE his garages, locked for safety until I was able to come and get it. I plan to get it tomorrow but having someone who knew me less than hour offer something like this was WELL beyond what anyone could expect from a business owner let alone their every day neighbor.

Long story short, I bought the car and called John to see if his offer stood. He told me to come on by, shook my hand, gave me his cell number and told me to call him when I’m there to get it out of the garage.

If this shop wasn’t 2 hours away from my house I’d be driving there for all my services. It’s not everyday you find such caring people. I get the feeling from the many regulars walking in and out, that this small gesture is an indication of the type of people John and his family are. Thoughtful, empathetic, caring and just flat out honest...

Absolute A+, John. THANK YOU SO MUCH. My faith in humanity is RESTORED. Do NOT overlook this place or these people. After 40 years in business, it’s no wonder they’ve become a staple in their local community.

See you soon...</review>

<user_name>Renee Whitney</user_name><Text>I was towed in, live in NV, engine stalling out. They tested my system and discovered my crank sensor was stalling me out.  Got it replaced and motor ran great again and arrived back in NV that evening.

< username>
Sean Hall<//username>
<time>1598287377498<//time><Rate>1</Rate>< Text>
I took my car to this shop needing the rear rotors and pads replaced on my car. I just had surgery on my right should and couldn't do the work myself, yet I had the rotors and pads to get the job done. The shop told me 'we cannot warranty the work because you're providing the parts therefore we won't do it'. I told them, 'that's fine, I don't need a warranty I just need the work done'. They still wouldn't do it.

Many shops, like this one,  employ this policy under the pre-text of "we cannot warranty the work". This is a lie, here's why:
-Customers can and do assume responsibility for the parts they provided(If you provided replacement parts they are yours, your property, your responsibility - common sense).
-California Bureau of Automotive Repair(BAR) does not require shops to warranty "outside parts"(BAR requires work performed to be done properly).
-When a component fails, its *obvious* if the labor performed or the part itself caused the failure.

The real reason some shops have this policy? The shop puts profit ahead of service and require all parts be supplied by the shop.

Anyway, that's my experience with this shop; I ended up taking my car to another shop.< /Text>

<Resp>{'time': 1620846091950, 'text': "I am sorry your wait was so long. To be clear, we are not a first come first serve clinic. We are an emergency clinic, cases are seen in order of severity which is why cases may have arrived after you yet been seen before your cat, who needed to be seen, but was stable. Last night we opened our doors at 6:00pm. I had one doctor, 5 technicians, and 3 receptionists. By 7:00pm all 5 exam rooms were filled and we had 15 people checked in and waiting in the parking lot.  The receptionists do their best to estimate wait times but sadly one life threatening case impacts that estimate.  Our over-night doctor arrived at 8:00pm which helped us get through our cases. Emergency veterinarians are in extremely short supply and the burn-out rate is skyrocketing. We understand your frustration and are doing the best we can with the staff we have.  We appreciate everyone's patience, however you always have the option to go elsewhere  and we often provide alternative emergency clinics numbers and addresses."}</Resp><GmapID>0x80dcadb016a7cbbf:0x5e53d00f2d0a3f57</GmapID><Time>1620800580862<//Time><user>105910640648446615812</user>< Pictures>

< text>
I haven't been so impressed with a medical business in a long time. Yes, the wait time is long, but so are all emergency vets (I called all of them). This place is staffed by angels. There are at least 1-2 office phones ringing off the hook literally every second yet the front desk staff never looks panicked, never rushes, never get snappy. <UserId.>114928296571542914699</UserId.>< username>
El Cid Campeador< /username>
<time>1608411985118<//time><rate>1< /rate>< Review>
It's been two days since our little guy passed away yet I can't find peace. The pain of feeling guilty for not being able to help the little being that depended on me is unbearable.
His name was Marshmallow. He was a tiny 2 month old mix of teacup Chihuahua and a Shih tzu, only 2 lbs in weight.
His mother had a difficult labor and only two boys survived, him and his brother. They were the best buds.
I don't know how in the world he became sick with Parvo.  He had no interaction with the outside world.
First day we tried to control the vomiting until he started to have bloody diarrhea. That night we took him and his bother to the Emergency.
Living on a fixed income we couldn't afford much so we opted out for subdermal fluids.
I can't understand, I refuse to understand why Dr. didn't administer the little guy any antibiotics for the secondary bacterial infection.
It would be an additional $60 in cost that could have saved his life.
Seeing that he is only 2 lbs, that his temperature is low which means that his immune system is not fighting at all, seeing that he is shedding his intestinal lining and not add a good dose of antibiotics to the subdermal fluids is simply heartbreaking.
We were told to head over to our regular vet which is what we did but our vet was booked that day. We called another vet that we used years ago and were told they are not taking new patients. Couldn't return to emergency clinic as during the day they are closed.
Tried to buy penicillin at the feed store to administer it ourselves (which we did years prior to save our dog after doctors gave up on her).
Were told that due to new laws in CA feed stores no longer allowed to sell injectable penicillin.
So the little guy was left without antibiotics for 12 hours allowing infection to set in.
I can not believe that the world can be so cruel.
Not until he passed away at the emergency that night did we realized that the same emergency Dr. runs a daytime clinic down the street.
How could this world be so cruel to the little guy I will never understand.
One failed to do the basics, others were too busy and CA made sure to add enough regulations leaving us with absolutely zero alternatives in helping our little guy.
My little Marshmallow, please forgive me.

P.S. Parvo is not a death sentence. Virus doesn't kill the dog. Dehydration and secondary bacterial infection does.
Animal needs to stay hydrated, needs antibiotics for a secondary bacterial infection and needs meds to stop nausia and diarreah.

Marshmallow's 2 brothers and a dad (all of whom had Parvo at the same time with him) lived with this treatment that they received at our daytime vet.

1)A bag of Lacted Ringers to take home (under the skin fluids that you can administer yourself to keep animal hydrated, very important)
2) Amoxicillin Drops (antibiotics for secondary bacterial infection)
3) Flagyl Drops (anti diarreah/antibiotic)
4) Reglan Liquid (anti nausia)
5) Nutri-Cal Oral Gel Dog (by Vetoqyuinol) (for nutrition)

Don't give up on your babies.
♥️✝️♥️< /Review>

None</pictures>

My family and I had to bring our cat in late Sunday night. We were greeted at the counter by Izzy who was very kind and attentive. We checked in and waited a few minutes. Our cat, Charlie, was immediately taken to a room to be examined. There were a few other families there with their pets but not too busy. After about 15 minutes, Dr. Williams came out to meet with us. She gave us some bad news about Charlie. His heart  rate and temperature were really low. His issue was very serious. Dr. Williams told us that the procedure to save him would be very expensive amd may not work. She told us she'd write up an estimate and give us time to think about it but reminded us that he was in really bad shape. After another few minutes, Stacy (vet tech) met with us and explained the estimate. Again, no pressure either way. She gave us a few minutes to think about what we would do. We decided to let Charlie go. They led us to a private room to spend time with Charlie. We were able to pet him and comfort him as he was medicated and put down. This was our second visit there and both times were excellent. We hated to let our Charlie go but the staff here was so thoughtful amd caring. They helped make this process less painful.</Review>

My son's cat, Vina, was suffering from a terrible malignant tumor in her jaw and there was no hope for a long term cure or successful treatment. Vina deteriorated rapidly and was barely able to eat and the tumor was actually pushing the teeth from their positions in the lower jaw. The difficult decision was made to euthanize next week but Vina showed visible signs of suffering and it was clear that it was no longer an option to wait.

The Animal Emergency Clinic opens at 6:00 PM and my son, daughter-in-law and I were able to walk in with Vina to a beautiful reception area with staff at the ready to help us. Vina was taken into the back right away while we checked in with the kind receptionist, Izzy, who waited patiently as I was unable to even speak being so distressed. My son was able to complete the check-in paperwork, a very efficient and brief process, and render payment so we could focus on Vina only.

The technician, Stacey, was efficient, professional, but also kind and compassionate. We were taken to a quiet room with soft lighting, a small water fountain which was soothing to listen to, comfortable seating with cushions, and a gurney covered with a soft blanket for Vina. Vina was carried into the room with the IV line in place. We were able to visit with her and offered any length of time to say our good-byes. Vina was calm, happy, and content and no signs of fear or anxiety.

Dr. Rios entered the room quietly and walked us through the process, relaxation medication in the line and then the final medication for euthanasia, with Vina's last memory being that of our comforting hands
holding her. Dr. Rios was very professional and calm but also showed tremendous compassion and empathy for our pain and the loss of our pet.

I am writing this review the night of our loss of our beloved Vina with the experience fresh in my mind. I am so happy that Vina did not spend her final moments in a cold clinic on a colder examination table with bright lights and loud noises.

I highly recommend this clinic if the sad decision is made to put a beloved pet to sleep as the environment is calming for the pet as well as the pet parents.

Thank you all, wonderful staff, Dr. Rios, Stacey, Izzy, and the technicians who helped us transition Vina from this life.

Highly recommend!<//Text>

We had to put our old man down yesterday. He made it to 18, pretty good for a big cat. The staff was compassionate and understanding and treated both him and us with care and respect.
They have a special room in their new location set up to be very calming and serene. It looks nothing like a vet's office and was a nice place to spend our last time with our boy.
They even have a back door that you can sneak out of when you are done so you don't have to go back through the lobby with tears in your eyes.
Their prices are the best around, too.
Highly recommend if you have to make that final choice for your beloved pet.< /text>

I’m not going to leave a distasteful review about the whole office when really my problem is with the one veterinarian that supposedly “treated” my cat. Instead, I’ll leave a review about my experience in this office step-by-step and what ultimately lead to me having to put my cat down today at 9:30am (at a completely different veterinarian). Please understand, I am not blaming these people for the death of my cat, I am explaining the mistreatment my cat received while in this office and the unnecessary suffering he endured for the remainder of the night. I took my cat in around 7:30 PM June 9, 2019. When I brought him in he was clearly in pain crying at every touch or movement. I explained I was not sure the last time he was vaccinated, probably 2-3 yrs prior, but that this was not normal behavior. He had blood coming from somewhere, nose or mouth but hard to tell which. I could only see a small amount periodically because he was drooling so much and it was frothy. I explained that he was both an indoor/outdoor cat, but he preferred to be outside. The lady at the desk heard his cries and took him in immediately because she saw his discomfort and knew something was wrong. She was not even a veterinarian and she could see that much. They did not even allow me to stay with my cat during the exam, or subsequent treatment. I found this odd, and disturbing. I have always been allowed to accompany my animals AT EVERY OTHER VET. After the initial exam, the vet came out and spoke to me and informed me the first step was to do a blood test and in case he’d been hit by a car, maybe x-I agreed to the blood test but denied the x-rays because I knew the possibility of a broken bone was very unlikely due to the fact he never leaves our property. NEVER. It’s an acre, surrounded by fences. When she came in she was very obviously judging me over the fact that he hadn’t been vaccinated in awhile and therefore continued to be dismissive of everything else I expressed concern for. I was concerned that he was suffering, both because he was crying out and he couldn’t walk, was frothy at the mouth with a bloody discharge he was gagging and choking. To set me straight, she stated and I quote “him crying means nothing, cats cry when they’re hungry”!
I understand what she was attempting to say, but believe me, I know his hungry cry, and I certainly didn’t take him to an Emergency Vet, knowing what it may cost because HE WAS HUNGRY!! Instead of listening to what I had to say and allowing me to give her some history of my cat, that was most definitely relevant, she took her time to explain to me that he was a potential danger to all other cats around him, (I had expressed concern he may have an infection because he constantly fights with strays from our neighborhood) I can appreciate her concern for the stray cats, they are still animals who need care but they aren’t the cat who I was paying her to examine. She initially stated that there was very little sign of infection in his blood, and said she was unsure if it was bacterial and could be treated with antibiotics. She also suggested she would need to run additional tests for Feline leukemia and Feline Aids. I of course okayed that test as well, I truly believed my cat was suffering. I had explained that no matter how hard it would be for me, I would put him down to avoid him suffering. She also told me she did a full inspection for any type of wound and found nothing on his body.  After about an hour and a half the clerk comes back to me to sign paperwork saying they were sending my cat home with antibiotics for a bacterial infection, at this point nobody had told me about the second test results I had to ask to which nobody knew the answer to but they were ready to send my cat home anyway. At this point I signed the paperwork to get him out of there because they would not let me see him, they only told me that The second test came back negative so it had to be an infection. They said they gave him an injection (no idea what, getting answers from these people is no easy task) PLZ READ PT2!!!</Review>

< text>
The staff immediately recognised an emergency situation with my dog who I love like family, I got there filled out some forms and as soon as i finished a woman staff member rushed to helped me get him onto a gerny to move him inside. We got a room straight away and a nurse checked his temp as soon as we settled in and then went and got my little guy some blankets to help warm him while we waited. It only took the veterinarian a minute to get into our room, she looked him over gave us a quick run down on what it could be and how severe each scenario would be. Got him in for an x-ray within 15 minutes of pulling into the parking lot, one of the nurses was nice enough to let me walk with them into the x-ray room and pet and talk to him for a little longer to calm my own nerves more so than his haha, After the x-rays came out they didn't show any major issues so the veterinarian explained what that meant, our next steps and options. After all the testing and when treatment was started and he was more stable they allowed my girlfriend and I to stay in the back with our dog for quite some time just petting and talking to him. We asked if he could have a blanket and the nurse took his temp again then happily got him a very large comfortable blanket. After we Said our goodbyes for the evening I drove home and called them to see if there was any updates. The nurse checked and in a timely and professional manner gave an update on my dog's wellbeing and any changes in his demeanor. This morning I went to pick him up, enroute there I called and asked how he was doing and got the same professional answers. Upon arriving to pick him up I paid and got him while only waiting a few minutes. At times I can be a very demanding person especially when it involves my dog, and in a very hard time the staff was calm, sweet, collected, informative, and clearly working towards the comfort and health of my dog. It was a little pricey so make sure to ask prior to agreeing to services. Thank you to everyone working there, you saved my family member.<//text>

< Text>
We have used these folks off and on for years for our pet emergencies.

We were tending pets at a friends house (family trip) on a recent weekend and on Friday evening (just after the local vets closed) we discovered a frayed wire embedded into one of the dogs rear feet. The cable was wrapped around both legs and appeared to be wrapped around the dew claw to the point of pinching it off.

We took our unhappy dog to the AEC where they rushed us into a room (after looking at the foot) and then send the dog for care while then getting our information.

We were surprised when they brought the dog back in less that 3 minutes in her normal happy state!

The vet told us that the wire was only wrapped with hair and was a simple matter of carefully cutting the hair to remove the wire, and that there was no charge! Have a nice day!

I told my daughter that I would write them a letter or review and figured that I could do it here where people can see it, so yes I do recommend the Animal Emergency Clinc in Grand Terrace Ca.

Perk<//Text>

All of the 5 star reviews that are posted are from employees in the Los Angeles office. My family attempted to work with their office in San Diego, and it has been horrible. <userid>110468371906002056433</userid><user_name>Josue Lopez</user_name><Time>1501820011656<//Time><rating>1<//rating><review>(Translated by Google) My respects to this attorney and his vast experience in these matters, but unfortunately not to the rest of the San Diego, CA team. We made a call for a free consultation, we made the appointment, we arrived 10 minutes before and they saw us an hour later.

I have DACA and I entered the country with INSPECTION through a tourist visa that expired and I stayed here. Currently I and my partner are about to get married and she is an American citizen, a fact that can give me permanent residence. We talked about it with the person who attended us in San Diego and he told us that in order to do the process, we had to do it from my country of origin, which would have to leave the country and re-enter with advance parole, when in reality it I can do from this country just by adjusting the status without having to leave. Unfortunately he misled the fact that all DACA recipients entered without inspection and need to return to their country of origin.

Worst of all, is that due to lack of experience from having too many people on the team who are very YOUNG, they ended up giving us the total cost of this case that would be $ 10,000 dollars ...

I would give 5 stars to the great lawyer Eric Price, but sadly the team that is part of it prevented me.

Greetings and investigate the case of each one well.

Yo tengo DACA y entre al pais con INSPECCION por medio de una visa de turista que se me vencio y me quede aqui. Actualmente yo y mi pareja estamos apunto de casarnos y ella es ciudadana americana, hecho que me puede dar residencia permanente. Hablamos sobre eso con la persona que nos atendio en San Diego y nos dijo que para poder hacer el proceso, teniamos que hacerlo desde mi pais de origen, cosa que tendria que salir del pais y volver a entrar con advance parole, cuando en realidad lo puedo hacer desde este pais con solamente adjustar el estatus sin necesidad de salir. Lamentablemente confundio el hecho que todos los recipientes de DACA entraron sin inspeccion y necesitan volver a su pais de origen.

Lo peor de todo, es que a falta de experiencia por tener a demasiadas personas en el equipo que son muy JOVENES, terminaron dandonos el costo total de este caso que seria $10,000 dolares....

They don't inquire or listen, because they don't care and they are unprofessional (maybe not all, but in this very case). I was very upset and just walked out. I can't stand such prejudiced, superficial approach, it only adds to the health issues, that you already have, makes you not want to ever see doctors again, because they don't consider even the implications and the impact of their judgemental, mercenary attitude on your overall wellbeing. Good for nothing, but more damage such " doctors" are. After all I didn't choose to be born with condition that is managed only by few meds, all of which are controlled substances. <resp>None< /resp>< Text>
Like many of the reviews left already, I also have had to deal with rude nurses in the E.R. It isn't what anyone expects to be confronted with when seeking help. I on the other hand understand their frustrations with dealing with so many people seeking attention or seeking meds. Not everyone is taking advantage, but the people who are taking advantage are the ones to blame for the staff having their guard up and suspecting. The bad attitude is NOT okay, but I understand. As far as the service goes I been there several times and not once have waited longer than thirty minutes, always got the necassary treatment, and always left better than i was when I arrived. I have made only one complaint there in the several years of going there and made even more compliments. This isn't a hotel to be held to 5 star hospitality standards. It is a very busy hospital with most staff working 12-14 hour shifts a day with one day off a week. This hospital truly is a great hospital with knowledgeable and caring staff. I highly recommend this hospital to anyone in the area.</Text>
